    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>Walter</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>I don‚Äôt know why you do that. It doesn‚Äôt do anything.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>JEANNIE stops packing the pack of cigarettes. Stares at WALTER for a beat, then unravels the rapper and takes one cigarette out.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>Jeannie</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>It condenses the tobacco, moron. You‚Äôre more on then‚Äî</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>Walter</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>‚Äîoff, I know. Also, really doesn‚Äôt make any sense.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>Jeannie</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>Get the fuck outta the kitchen.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>WALTER grabs a cigarette from JEANNIE‚Äôs open pack, now discarded on the table.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>He exits the frame.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>Jeannie (cont‚Äôd)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>They say that woman are naturally more mature than men are, and they, whoever ‚Äòthey‚Äô are, are  most definitely right. Therefore, it makes sense to date younger if you‚Äôre a woman. Sweetie, date younger, never date no 25 years younger, let me be testament to that. I‚Äôm raising a second son. The only good thing: he‚Äôs no shlep in the bedroom. Anyway. Let me see that card. Where did I put it?</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>El does not react until the final question. She gestures towards the pile of mail on the kitchen table.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>Jeannie</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>I‚Äôd rather a little girl not have my cellphone number, so sorry. And yeah, you can‚Äôt record this either. CIA taking preteens now?</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>El writes on paper: ‚Äúit is just for the interview.‚Äù</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>Jeannie</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>This is not an interview, sweetie. I just wanna let you know what I think of that little skank. Everyone should know the level of slut we have living in this apartment complex. You ever see how she leaves the house all dolled up, bare stomach, her ass cheeks hanging out of her shorts, mile high fuck-me pumps. Turning every guy‚Äôs head. Sickening.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>El writes on paper: ‚Äúshe died last night.‚Äù</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>JEANNIE reads the note, she lights another cigarette.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>Jeannie</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>Can‚Äôt say I‚Äôm surprised. Let me tell you something, and let me tell you, ‚Äòthis something‚Äô is not a something I go yapping my mouth about everywhere‚ÄîI know someone when they are on the path of destruction. Boy, do I know it well. When were you born, sweetie?</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>El writes on paper: ‚Äú2003.‚Äù</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>JEANNIE stands up and makes herself a martini, then sits back down.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>Jeannie</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>Oh, my god. I can‚Äôt believe there are people too young for this to even have taken place in their lifetime. 9/11? Twin towers? Well, a bunch of Paki fucks crashed our own planes into a set of twin skyscrapers in the City. New York City, that is. I used to work in a shoe store on the third floor of the South tower. Our family would always set our clocks ahead so we thought we were already late and we‚Äôd rush and still be late. So I missed the ferry that morning, and I watched those planes take down these buildings. My husband, not that little shit Walter, my husband, dear Jeffrey, was a fireman, he started work the night before, and then worked three days straight after. Poor guy was sick. And yeah, both of us knew a lot of people who died that day, and even both of us survived that day, Jeff didn‚Äôt really. He was never the same again. Physically and you know‚Äî</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>(she points to her head)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>‚Äîor in here.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>JEANNIE finishes the last gulp of her martini, stands to make another, then sits back down.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>Jeannie</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>I knew he was dead for a long time. I thought I did anyway. Until I heard the sound of Jeff blowing his head off.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>(long pause)</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>Well, none of your horror movies do that image justice.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>JEANNIE finished another last gulp of her martini, stands, and moves towards the counter, before turning to El and says:</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>Jeannie</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>El, Sheen was just another person circling the drain. Don‚Äôt worry about saving people from falling off the edge or you‚Äôll slip too.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>Cut to:</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>Int. El‚Äôs apartment / El‚Äôs bedroom - evening</Text>
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Type="Action">
      <Text>CLOSE on El‚Äôs LAPTOP SCREEN: she checks her email, and has received responses from all of the COLLEGE KIDS next door. They are free tonight at 10pm.</Text>
    </Paragraph>
